      "iron_oxide_rust_gives_mars_its_red_col": "Iron oxide (rust) gives Mars its red color.",
      "saturn_s_density_is_less_than_water_0_": "Saturn’s density is less than water (0.687 g/cm³)!",
      "olympus_mons_on_mars_is_21_9_km_high_n": "Olympus Mons on Mars is 21.9 km high — nearly 3x Everest!",
      "neptune_s_winds_reach_2_100_km_h": "Neptune’s winds reach 2,100 km/h!",
      "earth_s_magnetic_field_deflects_charge": "Earth’s magnetic field deflects charged solar particles. The ozone helps with UV, but the magnetosphere is the primary shield!",
      "the_iau_s_2006_definition_requires_pla": "The IAU’s 2006 definition requires planets to clear their orbital neighborhood of other debris.",
      "also_called_the_goldilocks_zone_not_to": "Also called the \"Goldilocks zone\" — not too hot, not too cold for liquid water on the surface.",
      "the_moon_rotates_exactly_once_per_orbi": "The Moon rotates exactly once per orbit — this synchronization is caused by tidal forces over billions of years.",
      "opportunity_rover_found_hematite_blueb": "Opportunity rover found hematite \"blueberries\" — minerals that only form in water. Orbital photos show ancient river deltas!",
      "venus_is_hotter_462_c_vs_430_c_mercury": "Venus is hotter (462°C vs 430°C)! Mercury has no atmosphere to trap heat. The greenhouse effect matters more than distance.",
      "gas_giants_have_no_solid_surface_they_": "Gas giants have no solid surface! They’re mostly hydrogen and helium gas that gradually gets denser toward the core. A probe would sink endlessly.",
      "earth_s_distance_from_the_sun_doesn_t_": "Earth’s distance from the Sun doesn’t change during the day. Noon just means the Sun is highest in your sky. Earth is closest in January (perihelion)!",
      "jupiter_is_11x_wider_than_earth_and_1_": "Jupiter is 11x wider than Earth, and 1,300 Earths could fit inside it! The solar system has extreme size differences.",
      "pluto_is_still_in_the_solar_system_it_": "Pluto is still in the solar system! It was reclassified from \"planet\" to \"dwarf planet\" in 2006, but it’s still orbiting the Sun.",
      "the_asteroid_belt_is_mostly_empty_spac": "The asteroid belt is mostly empty space! The average distance between asteroids is millions of km. Spacecraft fly through without any risk.",
      "not_always_saturn_is_95x_earth_s_mass_": "Not always! Saturn is 95x Earth’s mass but surface gravity is only 1.06g because it’s so large and low-density. Weight depends on both mass AND radius.",
      "all_parts_of_the_moon_receive_sunlight": "All parts of the Moon receive sunlight! The \"far side\" is just the half we can’t see from Earth due to tidal locking. It gets just as much Sun.",
      "the_habitable_zone": "The Habitable Zone",
      "the_habitable_zone_or_goldilocks_zone_": "The habitable zone (or \"Goldilocks zone\") is the range of distances from a star where liquid water could exist on a planet’s surface. In our solar system, Venus is at the inner edge, Earth is in the middle, and Mars is at the outer edge. But having liquid water also requires the right atmosphere and magnetic field!",
      "the_greenhouse_effect": "The Greenhouse Effect",
      "when_sunlight_heats_a_planet_s_surface": "When sunlight heats a planet’s surface, the surface radiates heat (infrared). Greenhouse gases (CO₂, CH₄, H₂O) absorb this heat and re-radiate it, warming the planet. Earth’s greenhouse is +33°C (life-sustaining). Venus’s is +510°C (runaway). Mars has almost none (-60°C average). The amount of greenhouse gas determines the outcome!",
      "magnetic_shields": "Magnetic Shields",
      "a_planet_s_magnetic_field_creates_a_ma": "A planet’s magnetic field creates a \"magnetosphere\" — an invisible shield that deflects the solar wind (charged particles from the Sun). Earth’s magnetosphere protects our atmosphere and makes life possible. Mars lost its magnetic field 4 billion years ago, and its atmosphere was gradually stripped away. Jupiter’s magnetosphere is 20,000x stronger than Earth’s!",
      "why_isn_t_pluto_a_planet": "Why Isn’t Pluto a Planet?",
      "in_2006_the_international_astronomical": "In 2006, the International Astronomical Union defined three criteria for a planet: (1) Orbits the Sun ✓, (2) Has enough mass for round shape ✓, (3) Has \"cleared its orbit\" of other debris ✗. Pluto shares its orbital zone with thousands of Kuiper Belt objects, so it’s classified as a \"dwarf planet.\" This doesn’t make it less interesting — New Horizons revealed it’s geologically active!",
      "tidal_locking": "Tidal Locking",
      "over_billions_of_years_gravitational_t": "Over billions of years, gravitational tidal forces can slow a moon’s rotation until it matches its orbital period. Result: one face always points at the planet. Our Moon is tidally locked to Earth. Mercury is partially locked to the Sun (3:2 ratio). Pluto and Charon are mutually locked — they always show the same face to each other!",
      "searching_for_life": "Searching for Life",
      "a_biosignature_is_any_evidence_of_past": "A biosignature is any evidence of past or present life. Scientists look for: (1) liquid water, (2) organic molecules, (3) atmospheric gases like oxygen or methane that shouldn’t exist without life producing them, (4) energy sources. The best candidates in our solar system: Mars (ancient water), Europa (subsurface ocean), Enceladus (water geysers), and Titan (methane lakes).",
      "tour_guide": "Tour Guide",
      "guided_tour_for_beginners_grades_3_5": "Guided tour for beginners (grades 3-5)",
      "explorer": "Explorer",
      "self_directed_exploration_grades_6_8": "Self-directed exploration (grades 6-8)",
      "researcher": "Researcher",
