      "tolerance_receptor_desensitization": "⚠️ Tolerance & Receptor Desensitization",
      "with_repeated_exposure_postsynaptic_re": "With repeated exposure, postsynaptic receptors undergo downregulation — the cell reduces receptor density or sensitivity (internalization) to compensate for excess stimulation. This means higher doses are needed to achieve the same effect, driving the cycle of tolerance and dependence. Abrupt cessation can cause withdrawal as the nervous system has adapted to the drug’s presence.",
      "how_neurons_fire_the_action_potential": "⚡ How Neurons Fire: The Action Potential",
      "ion_chemistry": "🧪 Ion Chemistry",
      "at_rest_the_neuron_is_polarized_at_70m": "At rest, the neuron is polarized at -70mV. Na⁺ (sodium) is concentrated outside; K⁺ (potassium) inside. The Na⁺/K⁺ pump maintains this gradient using ATP energy (3 Na⁺ out, 2 K⁺ in).",
      "all_or_nothing_firing": "⚡ All-or-Nothing Firing",
      "when_stimulation_reaches_threshold_55m": "When stimulation reaches threshold (-55mV), voltage-gated Na⁺ channels open and the neuron fires at FULL strength. There is no “half” signal — it either fires completely or not at all. Stronger stimuli increase firing RATE, not intensity.",
      "recovery_cycle": "🔄 Recovery Cycle",
      "after_firing_na_channels_close_k_chann": "After firing: Na⁺ channels close, K⁺ channels open → repolarization. The membrane briefly overshoots to -80mV (hyperpolarization), creating a refractory period where the neuron cannot fire again. This ensures one-way signal travel.",
      "saltatory_conduction_signals_jump_betw": "Saltatory conduction: signals “jump” between Nodes of Ranvier along the myelinated axon, increasing speed from ~2 m/s to ~120 m/s.",
      "stimulation_lab_2": "⚡ Stimulation Lab",
